    "133346972": {
      "title": "Aboveground:Belowground phytomass ratios in Venezuelan pAramo vegetation and their significance",
      "abstract": "Phytomass determinations were made for the pairamo vegetation at five sites between 3530 and 4700 m altitude in the Venezuelan Andes. Aboveground values (living vascular plant parts only) were 59.5 to 377.5 g m-2, and aboveground:belowground (A:B) ratios were 1:0.4 to 1:1.0 at four sites and 1:1.4 at a site showing effects of grazing. These ratios are far higher than those typical of arctic and alpine vegetation, but they confirm similarly high values found in two earlier studies in tropicalpine vegetation. A model is proposed in which A:B ratio variations between vegetation types are explained in terms of two unquantified parameters: total annual stress is inversely related to vegetation stature, controlling A:B ratios through the requirement for supporting roots; predictable periodic stress or seasonality necessitates belowground storage of energy reserves. Vegetation types are located on a figure, in accord with available A:B ratio data. Tropicalpine vegA:Bet ration, being short and not growing in pronounced seasonal environments, is portrayed as having the highest ratio of all vegetation."
    },
    "86264421": {
      "title": "Tropical alpine plant ecology",
      "abstract": "\"Tropical alpine\" refers to areas within the tropics above the natural elevation limit of contiguous, closed-canopy forest. The habitat occurs in Central America, South America, Africa, Papua New Guinea, Irian Jaya, Borneo, Java, Sumatra, and Hawaii. Tenerife, in the Canary Islands, although subtropical, has an alpine zone ecologically similar to that in Hawaii, just inside the tropics. Treeline often occurs at 3400 to 3900 m (but see 60), and the upper limit of plant life is often at 4600 to 4800 m (25, 35, 36, 43, 45, 48, 56, 92, 94, 109, 136, 146, 147, 152, 155). The lower limit of the tropical alpine habitat is poorly defined both in areas where human disturbance has lowered or eliminated treeline (as in some parts of the Andes and Papua New G(uinea; 32, 62, 106, 132, 152), and in very dry areas (such as the western slopes of the central Andes and the northern slope of Mount Kenya; 25, 157) where treeline forest is naturally lacking. In these cases tropical alpine vegetation merges gradually with montane scrub, pasture, or desert vegetation. The general term \"tropical alpine\" includes regional terms such as \"paramo\" (mesic areas of the northern Andes), \"puna\" (drier areas of the central Andes), \"jalca\" (mesic areas in the transitional zone between the paramo to the north and the puna to the south), \"zacatal\" (the Mexican volcanoes), \"afroalpine\""
    }
  }
